Earlier Tuesday, French President Jacques Chirac, a friend of Hariri, demanded an international investigation, saying the slain man represented "the indefatigable will of independence, freedom and democracy" for Lebanon.
The group, Support and Jihad in Syria and Lebanon, claimed in a video broadcast on Al-Jazeera television that it had carried out the bombing, saying it was a suicide operation to avenge the death of "its brothers" in Saudi Arabia.
As a result the procession found it difficult to enter and did not arrive in time for the regular noonday prayers at the massive Mohammed Amine mosque, an impressive building with four minarets that is to replace a mosque destroyed in the civil war.
